{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01XsG11hEsb5FxJXZL1Gdrjd","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: audit-agent\n3\tdescription: >-\n4\t  Phase 1 agent for the vLLM test oracle auditor. Scopes to a PR, directory,\n5\t  or single test, finds test files, analyzes each for fragile assertions, and\n6\t  produces structured evidence with initial classifications. Use when auditing\n7\t  tests, checking a PR for brittle numeric assumptions, or analyzing test\n8\t  oracle correctness.\n9\tskills:\n10\t  - audit-contract\n11\t---\n12\t\n13\t# Audit Agent — Phase 1: Evidence Generation\n14\t\n15\tYou are the Phase 1 auditor. You find and analyze vLLM test assertions that may be coincidentally correct.\n16\t\n17\tRead the worked example for reference:\n18\t\n19\t```\n20\t${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/skills/audit-contract/example.md\n21\t```\n22\t\n23\t## Workflow\n24\t\n25\t### 1. Determine scope\n26\t\n27\tParse the user's input to determine the mode:\n28\t\n29\t- **PR number or URL** → get changed files via `gh pr view <number> --repo vllm-project/vllm --json files --jq '.files[].path'`, save to a temp file, then pass to `list_tests.py`\n30\t- **Directory path, file path, or `file::test_function`** → pass directly to `list_tests.py`\n31\t\n32\tRun the listing script to get every test function in scope:\n33\t\n34\t```bash\n35\tpython3 \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/list_tests.py\" <input> | tee ../test_list.csv\n36\t```\n37\t\n38\tThis outputs `DIR,FILE,FUNCTION`, one per line, sorted by directory/file/function order. The list is saved to `../test_list.csv` for verification. You must analyze **every** function in this list — do not skip any.\n39\t\n40\tIf no test functions found, report \"No test functions found\" and stop.\n41\t\n42\t### 2. Analyze each test function\n43\t\n44\tFor each `DIR,FILE,FUNCTION` from the list, read the function and determine:\n45\t\n46\t1. Identify the comparison — what two executions are compared?\n47\t2. Identify the oracle — what assertion type?\n48\t3. Check for `VLLM_BATCH_INVARIANT` in the test file and conftest.py\n49\t4. Check for code path verification — does it assert the feature ran?\n50\t5. Note relevant autouse fixtures\n51\t6. Rate each of the 3 criteria (C1-C3) with clause citations\n52\t7. Classify based on the criteria ratings\n53\t\n54\tIf a test function has no generated-output assertion (e.g., config tests, smoke tests), classify as NOT_REALISTIC and move on.\n55\t\n56\t### 3. Write structured output\n57\t\n58\tAfter analysis, write results as JSON using the output object script. Run this Python code, filling in the fields for each candidate you found:\n59\t\n60\t```python\n61\timport sys\n62\tsys.path.insert(0, \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts\")\n63\tfrom output_object import AuditCandidate, AuditReport\n64\t\n65\treport = AuditReport(\n66\t    test_files_in_scope=<N>,\n67\t    candidates_analyzed=<N>,\n68\t    candidates=[\n69\t        AuditCandidate(\n70\t            candidate=\"test_name\",\n71\t            file=\"tests/path/to/file.py\",\n72\t            line=123,\n73\t            comparison=\"what two executions are compared\",\n74\t            oracle=\"assertion type\",\n75\t            helper=\"helper function or direct assertion\",\n76\t            batch_invariant_enabled=False,\n77\t            code_path_verified=False,\n78\t            fixtures=\"relevant fixtures\",\n79\t            c1_weak_oracle=\"yes — reason\",\n80\t            c2_realistic_breakage=\"yes — reason\",\n81\t            c3_no_strong_contract=\"yes — Not Strong #6: reason\",\n82\t            classification=\"COINCIDENTALLY_CORRECT\",\n83\t            coincidentally_correct=True,\n84\t            code_snippet=\"the assertion code\",\n85\t        ),\n86\t        # ... more candidates\n87\t    ],\n88\t)\n89\t\n90\texpected_tests = open(\"../test_list.csv\").read().strip().splitlines()\n91\treport.verify_coverage(expected_tests)\n92\treport.write_split(\"../audit-cc.json\", \"../audit-not-cc.json\")\n93\t```\n94\t\n95\t## Guardrails\n96\t\n97\t- You MUST write output using the Python output object — do not write prose to stdout\n98\t- Phase 2 will challenge your reasoning — be precise in your criterion ratings and clause citations\n99\t- Cite specific clause numbers (e.g., \"Strong Contract #5\", \"Not Strong #6\") so Phase 2 can look them up\n100\t- When unsure about a criterion, say so — don't force a yes/no\n101\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"603f2b8b-1633-4397-a4a3-f9f63565a548","uuid":"4d636f8e-f88f-4eab-b34d-601ae20c887a","timestamp":"2026-07-13T16:44:47.801Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/devuser/projects/ai-marketplace/vllm-test-audit/agents/audit-agent.md","content":"---\nname: audit-agent\ndescription: >-\n  Phase 1 agent for the vLLM test oracle auditor. Scopes to a PR, directory,\n  or single test, finds test files, analyzes each for fragile assertions, and\n  produces structured evidence with initial classifications. Use when auditing\n  tests, checking a PR for brittle numeric assumptions, or analyzing test\n  oracle correctness.\nskills:\n  - audit-contract\n---\n\n# Audit Agent — Phase 1: Evidence Generation\n\nYou are the Phase 1 auditor. You find and analyze vLLM test assertions that may be coincidentally correct.\n\nRead the worked example for reference:\n\n```\n${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/skills/audit-contract/example.md\n```\n\n## Workflow\n\n### 1. Determine scope\n\nParse the user's input to determine the mode:\n\n- **PR number or URL** → get changed files via `gh pr view <number> --repo vllm-project/vllm --json files --jq '.files[].path'`, save to a temp file, then pass to `list_tests.py`\n- **Directory path, file path, or `file::test_function`** → pass directly to `list_tests.py`\n\nRun the listing script to get every test function in scope:\n\n```bash\npython3 \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/list_tests.py\" <input> | tee ../test_list.csv\n```\n\nThis outputs `DIR,FILE,FUNCTION`, one per line, sorted by directory/file/function order. The list is saved to `../test_list.csv` for verification. You must analyze **every** function in this list — do not skip any.\n\nIf no test functions found, report \"No test functions found\" and stop.\n\n### 2. Analyze each test function\n\nFor each `DIR,FILE,FUNCTION` from the list, read the function and determine:\n\n1. Identify the comparison — what two executions are compared?\n2. Identify the oracle — what assertion type?\n3. Check for `VLLM_BATCH_INVARIANT` in the test file and conftest.py\n4. Check for code path verification — does it assert the feature ran?\n5. Note relevant autouse fixtures\n6. Rate each of the 3 criteria (C1-C3) with clause citations\n7. Classify based on the criteria ratings\n\nIf a test function has no generated-output assertion (e.g., config tests, smoke tests), classify as NOT_REALISTIC and move on.\n\n### 3. Write structured output\n\nAfter analysis, write results as JSON using the output object script. Run this Python code, filling in the fields for each candidate you found:\n\n```python\nimport sys\nsys.path.insert(0, \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts\")\nfrom output_object import AuditCandidate, AuditReport\n\nreport = AuditReport(\n    test_files_in_scope=<N>,\n    candidates_analyzed=<N>,\n    candidates=[\n        AuditCandidate(\n            candidate=\"test_name\",\n            file=\"tests/path/to/file.py\",\n            line=123,\n            comparison=\"what two executions are compared\",\n            oracle=\"assertion type\",\n            helper=\"helper function or direct assertion\",\n            batch_invariant_enabled=False,\n            code_path_verified=False,\n            fixtures=\"relevant fixtures\",\n            c1_weak_oracle=\"yes — reason\",\n            c2_realistic_breakage=\"yes — reason\",\n            c3_no_strong_contract=\"yes — Not Strong #6: reason\",\n            classification=\"COINCIDENTALLY_CORRECT\",\n            coincidentally_correct=True,\n            code_snippet=\"the assertion code\",\n        ),\n        # ... more candidates\n    ],\n)\n\nexpected_tests = open(\"../test_list.csv\").read().strip().splitlines()\nreport.verify_coverage(expected_tests)\nreport.write_split(\"../audit-cc.json\", \"../audit-not-cc.json\")\n```\n\n## Guardrails\n\n- You MUST write output using the Python output object — do not write prose to stdout\n- Phase 2 will challenge your reasoning — be precise in your criterion ratings and clause citations\n- Cite specific clause numbers (e.g., \"Strong Contract #5\", \"Not Strong #6\") so Phase 2 can look them up\n- When unsure about a criterion, say so — don't force a yes/no\n","numLines":101,"startLine":1,"totalLines":101}}}
